\displaystyle\lim_{n \to \infty} n \ln\left(1+\frac{1}{n}\right)=1
\displaystyle n\to\infty,\frac1n\to0\implies \left|\frac1n\right|<1
t \to 0
t = \frac{1}{n}
n \to \infty
\ln(1+t) = t + o(t)
\ln(1 + \frac{1}{n}) = \frac{1}{n} + o(\frac{1}{n})
n \to \infty
n \ln(1 + \frac{1}{n}) = n \left[\frac{1}{n} + o(\frac{1}{n})\right] = 1 + n \cdot o(\frac{1}{n}) = 1 + \frac{o(\frac{1}{n})}{\frac{1}{n}} \to 1 + 0 = 1
|x|<1
 \ln(1+x)=\sum_{k=1}^\infty(-1)^{k+1}\frac{x^k}{k} 
